White House announces Biden will visit East Palestine to commemorate train disaster

by JACKSON SINNENBERG | The National Desk

Sun, February 11th 2024 at 10:06 PM
14

FILE - President Joe Biden meets with UAW members during a campaign stop at a phone bank in the UAW Region 1 Union Hall, Feb. 1, 2024, in Warren, Mich.     TOPICS:

    BidenEast PalestineTrain derailmentNorfolk SouthernWhite HouseSafetyLegislationChemical spill

WASHINGTON (TND) — President Joe Biden will travel to East Palestine Ohio on Friday, Feb. 16, to mark the anniversary and impact of the catastrophic train derailment, the White House announced Friday evening.

In addition to meeting with local and state leaders to discuss continued efforts to hold Norfolk Southern accountable, the president "will discuss his commitment to ensuring the people of East Palestine are not defined by this single event, and that his administration is delivering on the needs of families, businesses, and affected residents," according to guidance released by the White House Press Office.

East Palestine Mayor Trent Conaway, a conservative who does not support Biden, extended the invitation to the Democratic president at the behest of some of his citizens, but also says the visit will be good for his community.

Hopefully he can help us get a couple answers," Conaway told Fox News Sunday. "If he can't, we'll just move on.

This will be the first time Biden himself puts boots on the ground in the town on the Ohio-Pennsylvania border, which is still recovering from a massive derailment of a Norfolk Southern freight train which spilled tens of thousands of gallons of hazardous chemicals into the surrounding region on top of other chemicals aerosolized by the fires on the crashed cars. The president received substantial criticism from Republican critics, and some in the community, for not visiting in the immediate aftermath, instead dispatching Transportation Secretary Pete Buttigieg to serve as the avatar of the administration.

In a recent interview with WKRC, Buttigieg touted the tighter inspection rules his administration has put in place since the derailment. However he, like many in Washington, are putting weight behind and hope in the bipartisan Railway Safety Act back by all four senators from Ohio and Pennsylvania. That legislation aims at increasing safety mechanisms and regulations for freight trains, especially those carrying hazardous and our flammable material, mandating crew minimums on those trains and requiring research on more advanced designs for freight cars.

"This is a good, important, bipartisan bill," Sen. John Fetterman, D-Pa., said in a statement released last Saturday.

It’s a bill so necessary and commonsense that it has the support of both Democrats and Republicans in both chambers, President Biden, and even former President Trump. I can’t think of a better way to commemorate the one-year anniversary of this disaster than to pass a bill to ensure it won’t happen again.

While Norfolk Southern vows that is working to comply to and accept proposed new guardrails, the railway industry as a whole has been reportedly working against the bill, lobbying key members of Congress who oversee transportation to reject the bipartisan legislation. The Washington Post noted that over the past year, the nation's top five largest rail operators have thrown a combined $17 million at lobbying lawmakers as well as donating to other key lawmakers on Transportation Committees.

The bill is also expected to face an uphill battle in the Senate, despite its bipartisan origin and support up until now. The Hill reports that Senate Republican Leader Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., opposes the act in its current form. Other Republicans are also nervous about the law granting the Federal Railroad Administration certain safety powers, like overseeing the implementation of rail-side defect detectors and extending inspection times. Others are concerned about the the additional powers granted to the Department of Transportation to implement many of the news law's provisions.

"This should have been acted on before," Sen. Sherrod Brown, D-Ohio, told a Northeast Ohio public media station. "I'm pushing hard with Senator Schumer, the majority leader, Mitch McConnell, the minority leader, to get this scheduled on the floor. It comes down to the power of the rail industry."

Vance admitted to The Hill that he believes there are provisions in the bill he could write off to try and win more support but he is also sure that nothing will win over the hard holdouts like McConnell.

Residents of the village told WSYX that they are still concerned with the final stages of cleanup and whatever potential life has to move on after the last year,

“This town is very divided, very divided,” said Diane Parker, who lives close to the center of town.

They're still sweeping the roads dry, causing a lot of irritation,” Austin Huffman, a who works at his grandfather's hardware store across from the crash site, said. “They say it's all safe but there's a lot of people getting rashes and sickness.

Huffman is worried about the water too. He likes to fish and used to catch minnows to use as bait. He said there were fish kills in area waterways after the derailment and chemical release. But he said he’s also seeing improvement.

“I'm seeing the life coming back,” he said.

____________________________

WSYX'S Tom Bosco and the Associated Press contributed to this report.
